# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: decentralized-identity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] A **decentralized identifier (DID)** is a type of globally unique identifier that enables an entity to be identified in a manner that is verifiable, persistent (as long as the DID controller desires), and does not require the use of a centralized registry.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] DIDs enable a new model of decentralized digital identity that is often referred to as a self-sovereign identity (SSI).
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The DIDs are an important component of decentralized web applications.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] A decentralized identifier resolves (points) to a **DID document**, a set of data describing the DID subject, including mechanisms, such as cryptographic public keys, that the DID subject or a DID delegate can use to authenticate itself and prove its association with the DID.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] Just as there are many different types of URIs, all of which conform to the URI standard, there are many different types of **DID methods**, all of which must conform to the DID standard.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group maintains a registry of DID methods.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] A DID identifies any subject (e.g., a person, organization, thing, data model, abstract entity, etc.) that the controller of the DID decides that it identifies.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are designed to enable the controller of a DID to prove control over it and to be implemented independently of any centralized registry, identity provider, or certificate authority.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are URIs that associate a DID subject with a DID document.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] Each DID document can express cryptographic material, verification methods, and service endpoints to enable trusted interactions associated with the DID subject.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might contain additional semantics about the subject that it identifies.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might also contain the DID subject itself (e.g. a data model).
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] National efforts include the European Digital Identity (EUDI) Wallet as a part of eIDAS 2.0 in the European Union, and China Real-Name Decentralized Identifier System (China RealDID) under China's Ministry of Public Security.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The AT Protocol and applications powered by the protocol such as Bluesky use DIDs for their identity system in order to give users full control over their identity, including where their data is stored.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The protocol uses its own DID method, did:plc, as well as a general domain-based method with did:web.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] Persona is an identity verification company founded in 2018.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] Its product consists of uploading a government-issued ID and potentially taking a selfie to confirm the user's identity and give them a DID identity.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The service is used by the LinkedIn professional networking site, the Discord and Reddit social media networks, the Roblox video game platform, and the OpenAI artificial intelligence company.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is a privacy-focused digital identity solution developed by Polygon, a blockchain scaling platform.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] It leverages zero-knowledge proofs (ZKPs) to allow users to verify specific aspects of their identity—such as age or residency—without revealing underlying personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] This enables secure and private interactions with services that require identity verification, such as financial platforms, voting systems, or DAO governance, while preserving user anonymity.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is already being explored by governments and organizations seeking compliant and privacy-preserving identity systems in Web3 environments.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group developed a specification for decentralized identifiers to standardize the core architecture, data model, and representation of DIDs.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The W3C approved the DID 1.0 specification as a W3C Recommendation on July 19, 2022.
[src:decentralized-identity/decentralized-identifier] The Decentralized Identity Foundation (DIF) published a Dynamic Traveler Profile Generation Specification in June 2023, for use cases in the travel industry.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:decentralized-identity/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The TCP/IP protocol provides identifiers for machines, but not for the people and organisations operating the machines.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Services provide identifiers for the user, not the network.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The absence of reliable identifiers is one of the primary sources of cybercrime, fraud, and threats to privacy on the internet.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] With the advent of blockchain technology, a new model for decentralized identity emerged in 2015.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The FIDO Alliance proposed an identity model that was no longer account-based, but identified people through direct, private, peer-to-peer connections secured by public/private key cryptography.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Self-Sovereign Identity (SSI) summarises all components of the decentralized identity model: digital wallets, digital credentials, and digital connections.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] SSI addresses the difficulty of establishing trust in an interaction.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In order to be trusted, one party in an interaction will present credentials to the other parties, and those relying on the parties can verify that the credentials came from an issuer that they trust.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In this way, the verifier's trust in the issuer is transferred to the credential holder.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] This basic structure of SSI with three participants is sometimes called "the trust triangle".
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] It is generally recognized that for an identity system to be self-sovereign, users control the verifiable credentials that they hold, and their consent is required to use those credentials.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] This reduces the unintended sharing of users' personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] This is contrasted with the centralized identity paradigm where identity is provided by some outside entity.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In an SSI system, holders generate and control unique identifiers called decentralized identifiers.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Most SSI systems are decentralized, where the credentials are managed using crypto wallets and verified using public-key cryptography anchored on a distributed ledger.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The credentials may contain data from an issuer's database, a social media account, a history of transactions on an e-commerce site, or attestation from friends or colleagues.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Some blockchain identity systems use smart contracts as accounts with attachable data and permissions.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] ERC-725 is a draft Ethereum standard for smart-contract accounts with generic data storage and execution.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] LUKSO's Universal Profiles apply this model to on-chain profiles, combining a recoverable smart-contract account with public profile data for decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The European Union is exploring decentralized digital identity through a number of initiatives including the International Association for Trusted Blockchain Application (INATBA), the EU Blockchain Observatory & Forum and the European SSI Framework.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In 2019, the EU created an eIDAS compatible European Self-Sovereign Identity Framework (ESSIF).
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The ESSIF makes use of decentralized identifiers (DIDs) and the European Blockchain Services Infrastructure (EBSI).
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The Korean government created a public/private consortium specifically for decentralized identity.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In the German and European legal area, there are two regulations that are of particular importance for the topic.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] These include the eIDAS Regulation, which forms the most important framework for trust in electronic identification in the EU and is a fundamental building block of the digital single market.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The European Blockchain Service Infrastructure (EBSI) has provided the SSI eIDAS Bridge, as a technical implementation that enables a substantial level of trust.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The eIDAS SSI legal report also describes several scenarios of how SSI can fulfill the necessary regulatory conditions.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Furthermore, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) forms the legal basis for the handling of personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The EBSI GDPR Legal Report provides more information on this.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] SSI is a value laden technology whose technical operationalizations differ (see Technical aspects).
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Therefore, its implementations can vary significantly and embed into the very technology different goals, agenda, and intentions.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The term "self-sovereign identity" can create expectations that individuals have absolute control and ownership over their digital identities, akin to physical possessions.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] However, in practice, SSI involves complex technical infrastructure, interactions with identity issuers and verifiers, and compliance with legal frameworks.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The reality may not align with the perception generated by the term, leading to semantic confusion.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Critics argue that SSI may exacerbate social inequalities and exclude those with limited access to technology or digital literacy.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] SSI assumes reliable internet connectivity, access to compatible devices, and proficiency in navigating digital systems.
[src:decentralized-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Consequently, marginalized populations, including the elderly, individuals in developing regions, or those with limited technological resources, may face exclusion and reduced access to the benefits of SSI.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:decentralized-identity/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials can be issued by anyone, about anything, and can be presented to and verified by everyone.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The entity that generates the credential is called the *Issuer*.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The credential is then given to the *Holder* who stores it for later use.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The Holder can then prove something about themselves by presenting their credentials to a *Verifier*.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a verifiable credential operates in a triangle of trust, mediating between issuer and verifier.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Any role in the triangle can be played by a person, an institution, or a machine.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Note that because verifiable credentials can be created by anyone, the verifier decides if they trust the issuer.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The VC model places the holder of a credential at the center of the identity ecosystem, giving individuals control of their identity attributes.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The W3C VC model parallels physical credentials: the user holds cards and can present them to anyone at any time without informing or requiring the permission of the card issuer.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Such a model is decentralized and gives much more autonomy and privacy to the participants.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] This contrasts with the federated identity management (FIM) model, as adopted by SAML and OpenID Connect, which place the identity provider (IdP) in the central role as the dispenser of identity attributes and the determiner of which Service Providers (SPs) it will give them to.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] In the federated model, the IdP knows every SP that the user visits.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The data model for verifiable credentials is a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) Recommendation, "Verifiable Credentials Data Model 1.0 - Expressing verifiable information on the Web", published 19 November 2019.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The VC context, defined using the `@context` JSON property, is a JSON-LD construct that allows user friendly terms to be used for JSON properties.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] According to the VC data model, the value of many properties must be a URI.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Whilst these are globally unambiguous, (important for a global data model), they are not user-friendly.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Consequently, the `@context` property allows short-form, user-friendly aliases to be defined for each URI.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] This makes it much easier, and more user-friendly, to specify VCs.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Any new property can be added to VCs, as determined by the issuer.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Standard properties have been defined specifically as extension points.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a VC does not always have to be the subject of the credential.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] It is expected that most users will hold their own VCs, i.e., the holder and the subject will be the same entity.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] For example, when the VC subject is an infant, and the VC is a birth certificate, the holder may be one or both parents.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] No proof mechanism is standardized but the data model is flexible enough to support various existing cryptographic mechanisms, such as digital signatures.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Proof mechanisms that are in use include: JSON Web Tokens with JSON Web Signatures, JSON-LD proofs, and zero-knowledge proofs using schemes such as IBM's anonymous credentials.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Various protocols are specified for carrying VCs from the issuer/IdP to the holder, and the holder to the verifier.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] None of these protocols has become standardized.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Many people who are experimenting with VCs use HTTPS to carry VCs between the various parties.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] The security of verifiable credentials in the context of COVID-19 vaccination and test certificates has been questioned.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials have also been subject to usability concerns.
[src:decentralized-identity/verifiable-credentials] Some have likened anyone being able to issue a verifiable credential being like a shop clerk deciding if they should accept an out-of-state license as proof of age when purchasing alcohol.
